data.content:
## .NET 8 Migration: BackgroundProcessor

### Key Breaking Change

**`Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` in .NET Core+.** `ThreadAbortException` will never be raised. Your `catch` block is dead code.

### Migrated Code

```csharp
public class BackgroundProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private Task? _workerTask;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        _workerTask = Task.Run(() => ProcessLoop(_cts.Token));
    }

    private async Task ProcessLoop(CancellationToken token)
    {
        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            try
            {
                // Pass token so blocking calls become cancellable
                var item = await GetNextItemAsync(token);
                await ProcessItemAsync(item, token);
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                // Graceful shutdown requested — roll back partial work
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();
                break;
            }
            finally
            {
                FlushBuffers();
            }
        }
    }

    public async Task StopAsync(TimeSpan? timeout = null)
    {
        if (_cts is null || _workerTask is null) return;

        _cts.Cancel();

        // Wait for graceful exit with timeout
        var actual = timeout ?? TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5);
        if (await Task.WhenAny(_workerTask, Task.Delay(actual)) != _workerTask)
        {
            // Worker didn't stop in time — it's hung; log a warning.
            // There is NO equivalent to Abort() in .NET 8.
        }
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        _cts?.Cancel();
        _cts?.Dispose();
    }
}
```

### Critical Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Detail |
|---------|--------|
| **No forced termination** | .NET 8 has no `Thread.Abort()` equivalent. All cancellation must be *cooperative*. If `GetNextItem()` blocks forever without a `CancellationToken`, you're stuck. |
| **`volatile bool` isn't enough** | A blocking call (socket read, `BlockingCollection.Take()`) won't observe the flag. You must pass `CancellationToken` into blocking APIs. |
| **`Thread.ResetAbort()` removed** | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`. Delete any references. |
| **Sync-over-async risk** | If you keep synchronous `GetNextItem()`, wrap it so it respects cancellation (see below). |

### If You Can't Make the Blocking Call Async

```csharp
// Wrap a legacy blocking call with cancellation support
private Task<Item> GetNextItemAsync(CancellationToken token)
{
    return Task.Run(() =>
    {
        // Register a callback to unblock (e.g., close a socket, signal a handle)
        using var reg = token.Register(() => UnblockGetNextItem());
        return GetNextItem();
    }, token);
}
```

### Migration Checklist

1. Replace `Thread` + `volatile bool` → `Task` + `CancellationTokenSource`
2. Delete all `ThreadAbortException` catches and `ResetAbort()` calls
3. Thread cancellation through `CancellationToken` into every blocking call
4. Replace `Thread.Sleep` → `await Task.Delay(ms, token)`
5. Implement `IDisposable` to dispose the `CancellationTokenSource`
6. If hosting in ASP.NET Core, consider `BackgroundService` (inherits from `IHostedService`) which gives you `StopAsync` + DI for free
